SATIRE V THE PARASITE

The treatment of parasites and poor clients at the tables of rich patrons is a common subject in Roman literature. Plautus, Terence, and Martia] furnish good illustrations, and Pliny, Ep. 11, 6, gives an account of a dinner in most respects similar to the one here described. In Pliny, however, we have the description of a real occurrence, with none of the exaggeration which mars the page of Juvenal. On the Greek side, Lucian (De Mero. Cond.)furnisl1es the best parallels3 and in Eng- lish, Bishop Hall has a close imitation, even using the names of Trebius and Virro (Sat. V, 2).
